      "text": "A 48-year-old man comes to the physician because of a 2-month history of sore throat that is associated with difficulty swallowing. He says that his breath has recently “picked up a weird smell.” He has had no fever, weight loss, or difficulty speaking. He has gastroesophageal reflux disease and recurrent cold sores. He is sexually active with multiple male and female partners and uses condoms inconsistently. His medications are pantoprazole and topical acyclovir as needed. He smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 5 years but quit 20 years ago. He does not drink alcohol or use illicit drugs. He is 178 cm (5 ft 10 in) tall and weighs 98 kg (216 lb); BMI is 31 kg/m2. Vital signs are within normal limits. Physical examination shows an enlarged left tonsil with an ulcerous lesion but no purulent exudate. There is ipsilateral cervical nontender lymphadenopathy. Which of the following is the strongest predisposing factor for this patient’s condition?",
